prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: MSXiiiaRA16a1
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: Infrared selected sources: MSX A-D iiia sorted RA = 16 1st 25 sources in RA range

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
We ask for a single spectral window with sufficient sensitivity and spectral resolution to detect typical masers easily within the time on source. With one minute of observing (i.e., 40 sec on source), using the worst (5mm, 7th octile) water vapor and >30 receivers, assuming a 7 channel (5 km/s) detection requiresa channel rms of about 10-15 mJy to detect a typical peak flux of 50 mJy at 10sigma (or 7sigma with 20 receivers) in a 0.7 km/s channel. To set up the correlator we therefore choose 244 kHz frequency channels over 938 MHz dual polarization bandwidth for our primary SiO (2-1) v=1 line at 86.2 GHz. The total bandwidth (+- 1600 km/s) covers the full extent of probable Galactic line-of-sight velocities, although it is possible that other lines (e.g., SiO 2-1 (v=0)) may show up. The other sidebands are free to be chosen and we select the thermal 98.0 GHz J=2-1 (v=0) CS line for C/O ratio checking purposes. A third sideband is used to cover the SiO 2-1 (v=2) and (v=1) lines.
The continuum flux entered for the sources are actually the flux in the MSX-A band for reference. The expected maser flux entered to allow validation of the proposal is unknown, but we expect at least 50 mJy for detections. The linewidths are anticipated to be approximately 7 km/s, and the polarization 0%. Whereas we do not intend to use Hanning smoothing during the observations, when the data is smoothed to 5.6 km/s for detection purposes, this will result in an rms sensitivity better than 10 mJy/beam/channel.
The high data rate is a consequence of including two spectral windows covering the SiO (v=0) and (v=2) lines. If using this higher data rate would be a problem, we are willing to exclude these spectral windows. The advantage of including these lines is a possible higher detection rate.
The imaging requirement is modest for these point-like maser sources; the limited uv-coverage and snapshot mode would actually help in resolving out any extended molecular emission not related to the stellar masers. For this we slightly prefer to use the more extended configurations, but the compact configurations will do very well too. We do not require high-quality images, just cubes that can be searched for point-like line emission. The MSX positional accuracy is about 2 arcseconds (with a beam of 18 arcseconds) so the angular resolution and positional accuracy is not an issue for either configuration.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract:
We have initiated the largest ever survey of red giant SiO masers in the Galactic bulge and inner Galaxy. At the 43 GHz and 86 GHz frequencies of the SiO maser we are not hindered by extinction, and accurate stellar velocities (<1 km/s) and positions are obtained with minimal observing time. The detection of up to ~35,000 red giant SiO maser sources will yield numbers comparable to optical surveys, but with the additional strength of a much more thorough coverage of the highly obscured inner Galaxy. The number of sources will be large enough to trace complex structures and minority populations. The velocity structure of these tracers is to be compared with the kinematic structures seen in gas, complex orbit structure in the bar, or stellar streams resulting from infallen systems. Modeling of the bar and bulge dynamics will be done using the new kinematic information in the inner Galaxy region. Our survey will also yield luminous SiO masers suitable for orbit and parallax determination using VLBI.
We are successfully observing with our calibration scheme using the VLA at 43 GHz; we here propose to demonstrate its feasibility with ALMA in the southern sky at 86 GHz.
